3:["$","p",null,{"className":"text-muted-foreground leading-relaxed","children":"Aevo calculates FTM/USDT funding rates every hour based on the premium between perpetual and spot prices. The rollup settlement mechanism enables more frequent funding payments compared to traditional 8-hour cycles. Funding rates are determined by the time-weighted average premium during each hourly period. Settlement occurs on-chain while rate calculations leverage Aevo's off-chain order book for precise pricing."}]
4:["$","section",null,{"className":"mb-10","children":[["$","h2",null,{"className":"text-2xl font-extrabold tracking-tight text-foreground mt-12 mb-4","style":{"fontFamily":"var(--font-montserrat), sans-serif"},"children":["Why ","FTM","/","USDT","?"]}],["$","p",null,{"className":"text-muted-foreground leading-relaxed","children":"FTM represents a mid-cap L1 token with moderate volatility that creates consistent funding rate opportunities on Aevo. The token's correlation with broader L1 narratives generates predictable funding patterns during ecosystem developments. Aevo's smaller liquidity pool for FTM can amplify funding rate premiums compared to major CEX platforms."}]]}]
5:["$","section","0",{"className":"mb-10","children":[["$","h2",null,{"className":"text-2xl font-extrabold tracking-tight text-foreground mt-12 mb-4","style":{"fontFamily":"var(--font-montserrat), sans-serif"},"children":"Historical FTM Funding Rate Patterns"}],["$","p",null,{"className":"text-muted-foreground leading-relaxed","children":"FTM funding rates on Aevo typically range from -0.1% to +0.3% during normal market conditions, with hourly settlements creating more granular arbitrage windows. During Fantom ecosystem announcements or DeFi protocol launches, funding rates often spike above 0.5% as retail traders increase long positions. Negative funding periods usually coincide with broader L1 sector rotations or network upgrade uncertainty. The platform's pre-launch token capabilities sometimes create anticipatory funding distortions ahead of Fantom-related project launches."}]]}]
6:["$","section","1",{"className":"mb-10","children":[["$","h2",null,{"className":"text-2xl font-extrabold tracking-tight text-foreground mt-12 mb-4","style":{"fontFamily":"var(--font-montserrat), sans-serif"},"children":"Cross-Exchange Arbitrage Opportunities"}],["$","p",null,{"className":"text-muted-foreground leading-relaxed","children":"Aevo's hourly funding cycle creates arbitrage opportunities against CEX platforms using 8-hour funding schedules, particularly during the 6-7 hour gaps between major exchange settlements. The rollup's performance advantages enable faster position adjustments when funding rate spreads exceed 0.2% between Aevo and competitors. FTM's moderate trading volumes on Aevo mean funding rates can diverge significantly from Binance or OKX during low liquidity periods. Arbitrageurs often exploit these differentials by maintaining neutral delta exposure across multiple venues."}]]}]
7:["$","section","2",{"className":"mb-10","children":[["$","h2",null,{"className":"text-2xl font-extrabold tracking-tight text-foreground mt-12 mb-4","style":{"fontFamily":"var(--font-montserrat), sans-serif"},"children":"Risk Considerations for FTM Arbitrage"}],["$","p",null,{"className":"text-muted-foreground leading-relaxed","children":"Aevo's rollup centralization presents counterparty risks not found in fully decentralized protocols, particularly during network upgrades or validator issues. FTM's correlation with other L1 tokens can create portfolio concentration risk when running multiple funding rate strategies simultaneously. The platform's smaller liquidity pool means larger arbitrage positions may face slippage during rapid funding rate reversals. Bridge risks between Aevo's rollup and mainnet can delay position unwinding during volatile market conditions, extending exposure beyond intended timeframes."}]]}]
8:["$","$Ld",null,{"items":[{"question":"How does Aevo's 1-hour FTM funding cycle compare to 8-hour schedules?","answer":"Aevo's hourly funding provides more frequent arbitrage opportunities but requires active monitoring and higher gas costs for position management. The shorter cycles often result in smaller but more consistent funding payments compared to the larger, less frequent settlements on traditional exchanges."},{"question":"What makes FTM funding rates different on Aevo versus centralized exchanges?","answer":"Aevo's smaller FTM liquidity pool and combined options-perps environment can create more volatile funding rates. The rollup infrastructure also enables faster settlement mechanics, while the platform's focus on pre-launch tokens can influence FTM rates during ecosystem developments."},{"question":"What are the main risks when arbitraging FTM funding rates on Aevo?","answer":"Primary risks include rollup centralization concerns, lower liquidity leading to potential slippage, and bridge delays between the rollup and mainnet. Additionally, FTM's L1 token correlations can create unexpected portfolio exposures during broader sector movements."},{"question":"How do gas costs affect FTM funding rate profitability on Aevo?","answer":"Aevo's rollup significantly reduces transaction costs compared to mainnet operations, making smaller funding rate arbitrage profitable. However, bridge costs for moving funds to/from the rollup and potential MEV extraction during position adjustments should be factored into profit calculations."}]}]
